english:
  title: Gokgu Station
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The long road follows the coastline,
    A modest station rests at the mountain's foot.
    Bird paths wind through clouds in distant loops,
    Whale-backed waves wash and overturn the sun.
    The people here brim with generous warmth,
    Yet I, a exile, grieve alone.
    Tomorrow dawn I cross the great ridge,
    And never again shall I see my homeland.
  footnotes:
    - The poem uses natural imagery—bird paths, whale waves, and clouds—to evoke both the physical journey and the emotional displacement of exile.
    - The contrast between the kindness of the station's inhabitants and the speaker's inner sorrow underscores the alienation of the exiled traveler.
    - The final couplet suggests that crossing the great ridge will place an insurmountable distance between the speaker and home.
